begin
reserve k for Nat;
reserve l for Nat;
reserve n for Nat;
theorem
(( k mod n ) = ( 0 ) implies ( ( k + l ) mod n ) = ( l mod n ))
proof
assume that
A1: ( k mod n ) = ( 0 );
per cases ;
suppose A2: n = ( 0 );

hence ( ( k + l ) mod n ) = ( 0 ) by CKB2:def 1
.= ( l mod n ) by A2,CKB2:def 1;
end;
suppose A3: n <> ( 0 );

then consider m being Nat such that A4: k = ( ( n * m ) + ( 0 ) ) and ( 0 ) < n by A1,CKB2:def 1;
consider t being Nat such that A5: l = ( ( n * t ) + ( l mod n ) ) and A6: ( l mod n ) < n by A3,CKB2:def 1;
( k + l ) = ( ( n * ( m + t ) ) + ( l mod n ) ) by A4,A5;
hence thesis by A6,CKB2:def 1;
end;
end;
